cells: A decent learning pace would be 1 sticker a day (the workload decreases over time if you learn inverses)
Aim for 'pretty good' algs when learning 3-style comms for the first time, don't focus just on intuitive and easy to remember stuff nor go for perfectionism
The two key factors to a good comm are speed and consistency (it can be a bit hard to tell what algs are fast in the long run initially though if you aren't great with some fingertricks)
Learn at least all the 'basic' fingertricks (including S and E slice stuff for edges)
